Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz, studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow you to look for relatives among the stars, that is, those that arose from one cluster.
The results of their research were published in the journal Nature, and they can be briefly found on the university's website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas, preceding the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the stars-relatives.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from those of relatives in the cluster.
The simulation results of the astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts using a supercomputer simulated two streams of interstellar gas that together formed the cloud.
This object within a few million years under the influence of its own gravity is converted into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added paint-tags to the original gas flows and found that due to the rapid turbulent stirring in the cloud, a high degree of chemical homogeneity is achieved.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that you can search for stars-relatives by chemical composition, as well as to determine the possible regions of the formation of such objects.
