Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill under which the organization of trade unions is protected as civil law.
"Where are the trade unions, there are middle-class jobs," says Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat who co-chairs the Progressive Faction Congress.
That is why I am proud to introduce the Workers" Rights Act along with the symbol of the civil rights movement John Lewis.
This innovative bill will give workers the same legal capacity to discriminate against trade unions as other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of opponents of trade unions.
The amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to allow workers facing discrimination for engaging in trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive damages and punitive payments - a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is no doubt not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and co-authors of the bill offer is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that trade unions have been subjected in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country - Americans have once supported countries around the world to accept, expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution drafted to ensure that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in shaping a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, and to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans to write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek infringement of this right will not have legal effect; measures aimed at these purposes will be recognized as illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was the Chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which compiled the World Declaration on Human Rights, which in 1948 will be adopted by the United Nations as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect their interests."
By generations, the Americans took for granted the basic provision that labor rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and that the trade union should be protected as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King the Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the forces of the nation, but increased them.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack the trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how we should.
The official recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the expansion of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge temporarily blocks the law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of the Louisiana law, which his supporters say he is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
According to this measure, which was signed by the Governor of Louisiana Bobby Jinadl in June and was due to enter into force on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to receive patients in the hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that doctors can continue to do legal abortions, continuing to seek such authority.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally, continuing their powers," Judge John de Gravells wrote in a decision.
The hearing will be appointed within a month at which the judge will make a more permanent decision on the law.
Defenders of the right to abortion happily met this decision, the last in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it will give doctors more time to receive hospital powers.
"Today's decision ensures that Louisiana women are protected from an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who has filed a lawsuit to halt the law on behalf of three of the state's five clinics.
It was not immediately apparent whether the decision was to refer to the doctors from the two clinics that did not appear on the case, and also applied for admission.
Louisiana is part of 11 states that passed similar laws, and the courts recently found such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law that would shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to abortion, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that the laws on the powers of admission impose restrictions on doctors that are not necessary from the point of view of medicine.
Opponents of abortion object that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who has abortions in Louisiana has the authority to attend the hospital, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state are forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for their safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing this decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors doing abortions while their applications for admission were pending.
What will lead to the introduction of quotas on domestic products
At least half of the products for each type of goods in the range of retail chains should be of Russian production, according to the State Duma deputy from the faction "Fair Russia" Oleg Nilov.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, writes the newspaper "Izvestia."
The document will still be detailed to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. According to the rest of the groups of products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic producers," Nilov said.
Together with the amendments to the article "On the basics of state regulation of trade activities in the Russian Federation," the bill provides for the introduction of amendments to the Tax Code, which establishes a reduced VAT rate of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea to introduce a 50% quota in retail chains is included in a package of incentive measures for Russian manufacturers.
On the shelves will appear several times more domestic goods.
However, the initiative can have both a positive and negative effect, experts say.
According to the lawyer of the company "Taxovik," a member of the independent expert center "Public Duma" Sergey Litvinenko, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive, and will lead to growth.
In the positive will be agricultural producers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that the profit will grow.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian manufacturers will be able to increase the volume of their activities and sales, which will lead to the payment of higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will be developed faster, and contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, however, not immediately," the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break through to the shelves of local shops due to high competition from foreign analogues.
Now, after the embargo, this niche is freed and you can breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary inspections, food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, now there is a "browser moment" when the previous players have already left, and new ones have not yet arrived.
After almost a month, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the increase in prices for finished products," - said AIF.ru the first Vice-President of the all-Russian public organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors," Ph.D. Tamara Kasyanov.
Clearly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow to secure the sector for local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that are cheaper at the expense of subsidies from another state.
In other words, the struggle for the buyer will unfold between companies working under the unified laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanov notes, Russian manufacturers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots not in all articles.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to "reach" the share of Russian goods to half the range.
In this regard, there are growing fears that poor-quality goods will arrive on the shelves.
Perhaps, under the guise of produced in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be supplied," the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large retail chains, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that in such a scenario, foreign suppliers themselves will suffer, since the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas on domestic goods can affect consumers.
The fact is that some products of Russian production can cede in the quality of imported analogues, while stores will be able to raise prices for the second, as for a shortage of goods.
About the forgotten idea of import substitution in the early 2000s, economists again spoke in February of this year due to the incessant devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the backdrop of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is intended to oblige retailers to consider domestic manufacturers when ordering suppliers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently along the path of import substitution, and the system of planning production for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," says Deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is especially high, for example, in the dairy industry, where the share of imports is 25%.
Our farmers are really able to fully cover the shelves of Russian shops.
In addition, a powerful boost can be obtained by meat production.
As is known, the largest share of imports is preserved on beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% still falls on Russian products," - says Kasyanov.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas on domestic products will contribute to import substitution and can accelerate this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, because this requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that a full import substitution will not occur, but significant steps in this direction will be made.
In addition, it is not enough to establish quotas, it is still necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas will provide just such guarantees," - says the expert.
The untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video of the memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who forgive rural Australia face a higher risk of death from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
The researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research said the probability of dying 20 percent during the study in those living in regions and remote areas of the state than those living in urban areas.
NEVER RESEARCH: New drugs may slow lung cancer and ovarian cancer
The researchers tracked the medical path of women in seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that the woman's age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in the regions or remote areas of the state, the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not intended to determine why women living outside cities were more likely to die of ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that an untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment were possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly in large cities," she said.
Despite the improved quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of services on the road that would allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people undergoing treatment far from their home can help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that the long lifespan among women with ovarian cancer was rare, stressing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young mother from the Gold Coast, Elisha Nives, was told that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
