Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire immediately put an end to the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand for the lifting of the Gypto-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down their arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of indirect negotiations is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
More than 2,100 Palestinians were killed in the war, of which three-quarters were civilians, and at least 494 children, estimated by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel contests these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it did not provide substantial evidence to support the claim.
66 soldiers and six civilians were killed on the Israeli side, including one Thai worker.
