The program of recycling of cars resumed from September 1
From September 1, the program for car recycling will be resumed in Russia.
Until December 31, 2014, 10 billion rubles will be allocated for these purposes.
As explained by the head of the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation Denis Manturov, the money is allocated from the limits that have already been brought to the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation by redistribution from other areas of support.
The program will affect all cars older than six years.
The amount of compensation will be from 40 thousand for a passenger car to 350 thousand rubles for a cargo car.
Previously, there was already a similar program of car recycling in Russia.
The main difference of the current project, the minister explained, is that now it is planned not only to dispose of machines to receive a subsequent discount, but also the possibility if the car has reached the age of more than six years, to buy a new one at a discount when handing over the old one in the "trade-in" from the dealer, Interfax reports.
The previous federal recycling program, which was in force from January 1, 2010 to December 31, 2011, more than 16 billion rubles were spent.
Due to it, the level of production of passenger cars in 2010 amounted to about 1.2 million units (this is plus 101.4% compared to 2009).
Creator Coming Out Simulator will release a game about modern journalism
Game designer Nikki Case, known for the game Coming Out Simulator decided to release a game about modern journalism.
He spoke about his project in an interview with Kill Screen.
Case began work on the game a few weeks ago, but this fact became widely known only now.
The source of inspiration for the game was the events in Ferguson, where protests are now underway, which began after a policeman killed an unarmed black teenager.
The focus of the project, which does not yet have a name, will be how information coverage of stories affects their consequences.
The hero of the game, a civilian journalist, will need to photograph what is happening in the areas where there are clashes between the police and the population.
The hero can take a different picture of what is happening, which will affect the course of events.
If he shoots the scene so that the police will look like heroes, and the protesters - bandits, the police will begin to treat him better and let him go where the average person can not go.
If he covers the events differently, his photographs could turn peaceful protests into a massive riot.
The glasses in the game will need to be dialed with the help of a hero's Twitter, in which new subscribers will appear, if the photos posted there are popular.
The game has no name yet.
The release date and the platform on which it will appear is unknown.
Case, however, published an image showing how the event could change depending on how the photo about it was taken and processed.
In an interview with Kill Screen, Case explained that he had been contemplating the concept of such a game for a long time, but initially wanted to dedicate it not to the protests in the United States, but to the events in the Gaza Strip.
After he began collecting material for the game, the game designer realized that he lacked the knowledge and skills to illuminate the history of the region.
However, when he saw the media covering the events in Ferguson, he decided to make a game based on what happened.
Nikki Case is an independent developer who releases browser games.
His most famous project was the Coming Out Simulator, which was released in 2014.
This game, which tells about the events from the biography of Case himself, is devoted to how a bisexual teenager tries to tell homophobic parents about his relationship.
