The army controls the new government of Thailand
General Prayuth (right) appointed to the post of Minister of Defense Ruthew Wongsuwan (left)
The military ruler and Prime Minister of Thailand, General Prutiut Chan-Ocha, announced the composition of the country's new cabinet, in which more than a third of the posts are held by generals or retired generals.
Representatives of the army received key positions: ministers of defense, finance, foreign affairs and trade.
On Monday, Prayut Chan-Ocha was officially confirmed as prime minister after the king of Thailand officially approved the appointment of the head of the interim military government to the post.
The 60-year-old military officer who seized power in the country as a result of a bloodless coup on May 22 was the only candidate for the post of prime minister.
He was elected Prime Minister at a meeting of the Parliament.
Earlier, the army appointed members of the parliament.
According to Prayuta Chan-Ocha, the coup was the only way to maintain stability.
It was preceded by six months of demonstrations in which protesters demanded the resignation of Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra's government.
Officially, Prayut Chan-Ocha will be the interim prime minister as the military plans to hold general elections at the end of 2015.
However, there are fears that the military is trying to strengthen its power in the country.
The military came to power on May 22
against the background of complete paralysis of the civilian authorities.
The leaders of the main political parties were arrested.
Immediately after the military came to power, they arrested the country's leading politicians, including Prime Minister Yinglyk Shinawatra.
Some journalists and public figures were also detained.
The current political crisis is rooted in 2006, when the army removed his brother Yinglyk Shinawat Thaksin as prime minister.
Both are popular among the rural population, especially in the northern regions of the country, which has repeatedly ensured their success in the elections.
However, many middle-class and the capital's elite entered the anti-government movement, which has been paralyzing the country since November 2013.
