Genetic disturbance is often misdiagnosed
The British said she spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Carine Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charco-Marie-Tut disease (ShMT), a group of hereditary disorders that cause nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
Charitable organization CMT UK reported that the wrong diagnosis is a frequent problem among people with the CMT, because so little is known about this condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have a SMT that can cause motor symptoms, such as muscle weakness, insecure gait, and toes.
Patients can feel numbness or pain, and the condition is not cured and progresses, which means that the symptoms increase over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's (AF) ataxia, a condition for which was very bad.
Rogers thought she'd be chained to a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and she would die before she was 30.
The mother of two, who is now 51, said: "As a child, I knew that I can't do what others can do.
I fell every day, and I took more time.
I could never ride rollers or skateboards with other kids, and I was kidding a lot at school because I went and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten the feet, she looked into the medical card when her doctor left the room, and it was written there that she had an AF.
"I felt guilty because I put my nose out where I shouldn't, and so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about that state in the library and wrote to the AF Association," she said.
When I got the information back, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic that was possible.
I thought I'd be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that gap.
I went through it alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought and asked her doctor about it.
He just got up, hugged me, and said, "My dear, I don't think you're sick because you'd be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something that poses a much lesser threat to life.
After several genetic examinations, she was found by SMT.
"When he explained what a SMT was, I thought I pulled out a lucky ticket," she said.
The charitable organization of the UK has announced a month of information about the SMT to try to draw attention to this disease.
The tax burden on Washington zone entrepreneurs is growing as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
Tax bills for the state and local levels for companies across the country increased moderately last year, when the economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington zone - no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia paid a total of $27.6 billion to the state treasury and locally in the fiscal year 2013, 3.8 percent more than the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on the state and local businesses increased by 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after years that went through each other, when accounts declined in 2009 and 2010.
The tax levied by the state grew faster, 4.3 percent than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by a professional service firm, Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the tax revenue in the district, 56 percent, comes from taxes on entrepreneurs, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenues come from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
To a large extent, the growth in tax revenues is caused by a return to the previous level of real estate prices of companies, the researchers say that raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years, when the growth was less than 1 percent.
While a large share of these revenues are from large states such as California, New York and Texas, it seems that the same thing is happening in the Washington zone.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia have paid $10 billion in real estate taxes by state and local level last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 - an increase of 4.2 percent, compared to the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate costs has no similar effect on the growth of tax revenues by the state and at the local level in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one-fifth of the company's tax accounts.
The companies of Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of the tax accounts in the state and at the local level in the form of real estate taxes.
"What's going on in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a non-profit organization that doesn't pay property taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Taxation Center.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, such as income taxes, to pay for the same services that are available in other states.
The recent growth of tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
The revenues of entrepreneurs also seem to be improving, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared a state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has collected $1 billion in corporate income tax, the most in the region.
Although trends are directed in one direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level does not increase at the same rate in all three areas.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average of 4.3 percent, while the growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
Only in Virginia there was a rise in tax revenues below average, equal to 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while in the district it is relatively high - 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia's taxes are lower for state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than in Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbor from the south.
North Carolina recently signed a legislation cutting the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just like in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to achieve tax revenue targets next year, the law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs even to 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington zone seem to feel better and thus pay more taxes on the state and local levels, according to a recent study.
The Entrepreneurial Taxes paid as individual income tax by small business owners are the transitional structure that most small firms are based - in District Columbia, Maryland and Virginia up to $2.4 billion last year, with a much faster growth rate than taxes for entrepreneurs in general.
The researchers say the trend and increase in revenues from business taxes across the country are likely to continue this year, with revenues in turnover tax in state and local governments, which grew by 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington zone may lag behind, as the decline in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
