Deputies proposed to accelerate the entry into force of the law on personal data
If the initiative is successful, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015.
The State Duma introduced a draft law providing for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is placed in the database of legislative activities of the lower house.
Its authors were the deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevhen Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Fair Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (CPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more prompt and effective provision of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the preservation of personal data and observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, the entry into force of parliamentarians rushs, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed through the Internet.
It also makes mandatory the recording, systematization, accumulation, storage, clarification and extraction of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation, in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as indication of the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of the court's decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of the so-called "black lists" of sites-violators - an automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects."
This law was adopted by the state Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin from the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the Communist Party.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also one of the authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the law already adopted.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation, will have to pay for the lease
Commenting on the bill introduced today in the State Duma, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on information policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems for the postponement of the entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own repositories of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "Rostelecom, who has repeatedly said that they are ready to provide their servers and already provide their servers, from the Mail Group, from Western companies that already provide their servers."
"In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area," he added.
"If companies decide to implement the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problem - they will get technological opportunities for placement," Levin concluded.
Controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that if the bill is adopted, the Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services for air tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation the right to dispose of their own data imperatively determine that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation."
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be the creation of a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is carried out, systematization of his personal data.
In this case, he will be able to choose on which territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of such bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries led to the departure of global services and significant economic losses.
