Savings certificate will make name and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates for bearer, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban savings certificates for the bearer.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that bearer savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, because it is not necessary to make deductions to the Fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA).
The spicyness of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken due to small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to DIA, control 98% of the profile market.
Moreover, the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the Agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in the DIA, is that the customers of a small bank who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of his licenses are trying to get money in the DIA.
Some depositors, without sufficient financial literacy and buying savings certificates for the bearer, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in case of revocation of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when bearer certificates holders tried to recover insurance indemnity through the court," the DIA said.
The problem, of course, is far-fetched.
After all, no one will pay buyers certificates, since they do not have the right to reimburse from the state by law.
If the case was that the instrument was not insured in the DIA, along with it would be banned and metal bills, in which citizens' funds are taken into account in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but no one has yet to encroach on their existence.
The case is most likely that bearer certificates are a very convenient security that can actually act as a quasi-side.
At the same time, their movement is practically not subject to control: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer to any citizen, and before cashing, such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the bill prescribes that a savings certificate should be a nominal security that should be stored in the depository.
And in order to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to issue without the right to early repayment.
That is, an analogue of an irrevocable contribution is introduced, which bankers have long dreamed of.
