A Potential way to steal photos of naked celebrities
A massive hacking of star accounts may be made through a vulnerability in the Find My Phone app.
The potential scenario was described by The Next Web.
On the resource Github was published a script in Python, which allowed to select passwords for Apple's Find My Phone service.
This service allows you to track the location of the iPhone.
To access it, the same Apple ID login and password is used as for accessing the Apple iCloud cloud, from which photos of celebrities were stolen.
The script allowed the method of brute selection to recognize the password from Find My Phone.
In this method, all sorts of combinations of symbols are consistently introduced, starting with the most commonly used passwords.
The author of the script claimed that in the Find My Phone service the number of inputs of passwords is unlimited.
With the correct security system organization, after several unsuccessful attempts to enter the wrong password, the account must be blocked and reported to the user about the attempt to hack.
Due to the vulnerability, users have not received any reports of an attempt to pick up a password to their account.
The hackers learned the password from Apple ID and used it to access iCloud.
According to a Twitter account, the vulnerability was discovered two days ago, on Saturday, and a script program for the selection of passwords was written.
At the moment, the vulnerability is closed: after five attempts, access to the service is blocked.
The resource contacted the user Hackapp and he noted that the above vulnerability is typical for many services, but noted that it has no evidence that such vulnerability was used to access the account "stars."
