Putin granted Russian citizenship to Ukrainian pentathlon
Russian President Vladimir Putin granted Russian citizenship to the famous Ukrainian athlete Anna Buryak.
The relevant decree was published on the Internet portal of legal information.
Earlier this year, the athlete moved to Russia for permanent residence and appealed to the Federation of modern pentathlon with a request to give her the opportunity to play for the Russian national team.
In 2013, she won two stages of the World Cup, won the silver medal of the European Championship in the personal championship and became the world champion in the mixed relay, which is one of the new types of programs in this sport.
It retains the leading position in the current season.
According to the rules, in order to perform at the 2016 Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, it will need to obtain special permission from the Olympic Committee of Ukraine.
Anna Buryak is not the first Ukrainian athlete to change citizenship.
In July, Vladimir Putin decided to issue a Russian passport to chess player Ekaterina Lagno - a native of Lviv, who is a two-time European champion (2005, 2008), the world in blitz (2010) and fast chess (2014).
As part of the women's team of Ukraine, the athlete became the winner of the chess Olympiad in Turin (2006), the team world championship in Astana (2013) and the European team championship in Warsaw (2013).
The TFR stopped the investigation of the Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (Investigative Committee of Russia) has stopped the criminal case on the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the airline Red Wings.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the flight engineer.
Forensic examination showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of approach to the landing, failure of the crew to perform standard procedures at the landing, as well as the unintentional output of the engines to increased speeds of direct thrust.
The plane Tu-204 of the airline Red Wings, which followed the flight Prague - Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 when landing at the Moscow airport Vnukovo.
The aircraft rolled out behind the runway and caught fire.
At the scene, the commander of the aircraft, the co-pilot and the flight engineer were killed.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical facilities, where they subsequently died from injuries.
Three more flight attendants, hospitalized with serious bodily injuries, underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, serious bodily injuries were the driver of the car, moving at the time of the disaster on the Kiev highway.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
The transport prosecutor's office after the disaster conducted an inspection in Red Wings, during which numerous violations were revealed.
In February 2013, the airline's license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
