Anger turned out to be the most universal and functional emotion of man
The ardent facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and each organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but an additional means of expressing power and threats, scientists from Australia and the United States found.
They told about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly about them can be read in a press release from the University of California, Santa Barbara.
An angerous facial expression - shifted and downblit eyebrows, elongated in a thin line of the lips, bloated nostrils - the same in all cultures, and even blind from birth children who have never seen it, says the study's lead author Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists found that this emotion arose for effective dispute during the conflict.
The more physical damage one person can cause another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his conditions, and he brings it to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
The researchers have found confirmation of their other hypothesis: physically strong people are more angry and moving to handicrafts, consider themselves entitled to impose unprofitable conditions for them, and prefer forceful methods to resolve conflicts peaceful.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily a "emotion of bargaining," the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create an angry expression of the face should represent the angering individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thereby force him to accept his conditions as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated on the computer of a person where each of the seven elements of an angry person was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or the chin put forward separately did not make the face evil, the more physically physically participants of the study recognized the person depicted with such features.
The anger of man, as in animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one's own power, forcing him to accept and obey.
A person inflates the nostrils and presses the lips for the same purpose as the frog that inflates, or the baboon that demonstrates his flips.
"The anger "lakes" by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form that demonstrates the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry person is arbitrary, they all express the same thing," said anthropologist John Tubi.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV and radio company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate in 2014 from the federal budget 250 million rubles of the autonomous non-profit organization "Teleradiocompany "Crimea."
This is stated in the draft resolution of the government, prepared by the Ministry, which was familiarized with "Lenta.ru."
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of the modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment."
In particular, the allocated money is expected to be re-equiped hardware-studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server.
It is also planned to purchase a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (FOCL) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the framework of the federal budget provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959, broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the TV-and-patrol coverage of the TV and radio company accounts for more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Teleradiocompany "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
